Performance Metrics Comparison

Understanding the Metrics:

  • Brier Score: Measures accuracy (0 = perfect, 1 = worst). Lower is better.
  • AUC-ROC: Ability to discriminate between outcomes (0.5 = random, 1 = perfect). Higher is better.
  • Log Loss: Penalizes confident wrong predictions. Lower is better.
  • Expected Calibration Error (ECE): Average difference between predicted and actual rates. Lower is better.

Calibration Analysis

What is calibration?
A well-calibrated model means that when it predicts 80% probability, the outcome actually happens 80% of the time. The closer the lines are to the diagonal "Perfect Calibration" line, the better the calibration.

Calibration by Days to Expiry

üìÖ Calendar Days: "Days to Expiry" refers to calendar days (not business days) between the prediction date and option expiry date. This analysis shows how prediction accuracy varies based on how far in advance predictions are made.

Interactive Filtering: Select a stock and/or days-to-expiry range to see how calibration varies.

Calibration Error Analysis

Reading the chart: Positive values mean the method over-predicted (predicted higher probability than actual). Negative values mean under-prediction. Values close to zero indicate good calibration.

Sample Distribution

Note: This shows how many predictions fell into each probability bin. More samples in high-probability bins indicates confidence in predictions.

Conclusions & Recommendations

Key Findings:

  1. Bayesian Calibrated is the clear winner with best performance across all metrics (Brier Score, AUC-ROC, and Calibration Error).
  2. Exceptional calibration: The winning method has an Expected Calibration Error of only 0.0032, meaning predictions are accurate within 0.32 percentage points.
  3. High discrimination ability: AUC-ROC of 0.7764 indicates the model can effectively distinguish between options that will expire worthless vs. assigned.
  4. Large sample validation: Analysis based on 934,643 real expired options provides statistically significant results.

Recommendation:

Use the Bayesian Calibrated method for put option writing decisions. Its superior calibration and accuracy make it the most reliable predictor of whether an option will expire worthless.

Data & Methodology

Analysis Period: April 2024 - November 2025

Total Records: 1,073,731 option predictions

Validated Records: 934,643 expired options (87.05%)

Actual Outcome: 78.8% expired worthless (stock stayed above strike)

Markets: Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, and Finnish options

Methods Compared:

  • Weighted Average: Brier-score weighted combination of all methods
  • Bayesian Calibrated: Bayesian isotonic calibration with binning
  • Original Black-Scholes: Standard Black-Scholes probability calculation
  • Bias Corrected: Per-bin bias correction based on historical accuracy
  • Historical IV: Historical implied volatility accuracy tables
